<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900515-0013</DOCNO><DOCID>900515-0013.</DOCID><HL>   Wilfred American   Seeks Protection   Under Chapter 11</HL><DATE>05/15/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23</SO><CO>   WAE</CO><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Wilfred American Educational Corp., thebeauty-school operator, sought protection against lawsuitsfrom creditors by filing under Chapter 11 of the federalbankruptcy law.   &quot;The company was compelled to take this action&quot; for anumber of reasons, said Philip E. Jakeway Jr., chairman andchief executive officer. These include denials of thecompany's claims for reimbursement by the federal EducationDepartment. Wilfred derives much of its revenue fromgovernment student-loan programs. Also forcing the filingwere legal costs, operating losses and changes in governmentpolicies, Mr. Jakeway said in a statement. Wilfred officialswere unavailable for comment.</LP><TEXT>   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,Wilfred's shares closed unchanged at 56.25 cents. The BigBoard said yesterday that in light of the bankruptcy-lawfiling, it is reviewing whether to continue listing Wilfred'sshares.   The company's problems stem from an October 1988indictment of Mr. Jakeway and a number of other employees. ATampa, Fla., federal grand jury charged them with misusingfinancial-aid funds. In March 1989, nine of the otheremployees entered so-called Alford pleas, agreeing to pleadguilty to certain charges but denying any wrongdoing. Thetrial for the remaining defendants is scheduled for January1991.   In October 1989, a federal grand jury in Massachusettsindicted the company on mail fraud charges. The companydenied the charges, and the case is scheduled for trial inJune.</TEXT></DOC>